      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
Well that was weird. On Tuesday I  wrote a column=C2=A0saying it was=C2=A0u=
nlikely that Elon Musk will buy Twitter Inc. On Wednesday I left on a famil=
y vacation. On Thursday, for my sins, Elon Musk announced an offer to buy T=
witter for $54.20 per share in cash. 420 is a weed joke.I suppose this incr=
eased the probability that Elon Musk will buy Twitter? By a little? Yesterd=
ay Twitter=E2=80=99s stock managed to close down 1.7%, at $45.08, suggestin=
g that the market puts a somewhat lower probability on Musk buying Twitter =
after he formally proposed to buy Twitter than it did before.=C2=A0Musk has=
 some history here: In 2018  he pretended that he was going to take Tesla I=
nc. private;  he wasn=E2=80=99t, and eventually he  settled  fraud charges =
with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.=C2=A0Ordinarily if a bill=
ionaire chief executive officer of a public company offers to buy a company=
, the odds that he is=C2=A0kidding=C2=A0are quite low. When it=E2=80=99s El=
on Musk, the historical=C2=A0odds are, like, 50/50. (He really bought Solar=
City.)By Thursday afternoon, Musk went onstage at a conference=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94 honestly itself a weird thing to do in the middle of a hostile takeover=
 or whatever? =E2=80=94 and  said words that I think a connoisseur of merge=
rs and acquisitions, or of Elon Musk, will interpret to mean =E2=80=9Cokay =
sure I was kidding a little=E2=80=9D:=E2=80=9CI am not sure that I will act=
ually be able to acquire it,=E2=80=9D the billionaire entrepreneur said Thu=
rsday at a TED event in Vancouver. Musk said he has a Plan B if Twitter rej=
ects his offer, without offering more details. =E2=80=A6Musk said his inten=
t =E2=80=9Cis to retain as many shareholders as is allowed by the law in a =
private company.=E2=80=9DWhen Musk was pretending to take Tesla private, he=
 pretended that he was going to let all of Tesla's existing shareholders re=
main shareholders of the new =E2=80=9Cprivate=E2=80=9D Tesla.=C2=A0This is =
not a thing, and it was never going to work, but it was a nice friendly pro=
mise for Musk to make=C2=A0given that he was never going to take Tesla priv=
ate. And now he=E2=80=99s doing it again, saying that he will=C2=A0take Twi=
tter private while also keeping as many existing shareholders as he can. Su=
re buddy!One problem with Musk=E2=80=99s offer is that it is pretty low. Mu=
sk points out that $54.20=C2=A0=E2=80=9Crepresents a 54% premium=E2=80=9D o=
ver where he started investing in Twitter, and a 38% premium over where the=
 stock was before he announced his position. But Twitter was in the $60s in=
 October, and a lot of its big long-term holders seem unlikely to be seller=
s at $54.20. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98No board in America is going to take that nu=
mber,=E2=80=99 said Jefferies analyst Brent Thill.=E2=80=9D And=C2=A0here a=
re the Saudis:Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s Prince Alwaleed bin Talal rejected Elo=
n Musk=E2=80=99s bid to acquire Twitter Inc. for $54.20 per share, saying t=
he deal doesn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Ccome close to the intrinsic value=E2=80=9D=
 of the popular social media platform. =E2=80=A6A 2015 regulatory filing sh=
owed that Alwaleed, along with his Kingdom Holding Company, owned a 5.2% st=
ake in the social media platform. The Bloomberg Billionaires Index estimate=
s the position is now about 4.4% of Twitter.This is notable because, when E=
lon Musk pretended that he had financing to take Tesla private, the Saudi p=
ublic investment=C2=A0fund was=C2=A0who he  pretended was providing the fin=
ancing. In fact, on Tuesday I  made a grim joke about the Saudis providing =
pretend equity financing for Musk to=C2=A0 pretend to buy Twitter. Apparent=
ly not!To be fair to Musk, in this deal, he is not pretending to have finan=
cing. His offer to Twitter=E2=80=99s board is contingent on =E2=80=9Ccomple=
tion of anticipated financing,=E2=80=9D and when Musk answered questions at=
 that conference yesterday, one of the questions was of course =E2=80=9Cdo =
you have funding secured,=E2=80=9D and his=C2=A0answer was =E2=80=9CI have =
sufficient assets.=E2=80=9D Which means no! =E2=80=9CYes=E2=80=9D means yes=
. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m really rich, surely someone will give me the money=
=E2=80=9D means no one has yet.Now, he=E2=80=99s right that he=E2=80=99s ve=
ry rich, so it=E2=80=99s not at all impossible for him to finance this offe=
r. Musk will need about $40 billion to buy the 91% of Twitter that he does =
not currently own=C2=A0at $54.20 per share. He owns about 172.6 million sha=
res of Tesla Inc. stock, worth about $170 billion at yesterday=E2=80=99s cl=
osing price, plus more shares underlying stock options. He has pledged abou=
t 88 million of those shares to secure personal loans, but if he sold the o=
ther 84-ish million that would raise about $60=C2=A0billion after tax, more=
 than enough to pay for Twitter. That would be a pretty extreme move, thoug=
h. Musk seems to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0enjoy=C2=A0=E2=80=A6=C2=A0Tesla, and dumpin=
g half his stock would both (1) drive the stock price down a lot and (2) si=
gnal to the market that he has found a new toy and lost some interest in Te=
sla. That seems impulsive even for him, though he did sell about 10% of his=
 Tesla stock late last year  sort of due to a Twitter poll so it is certain=
ly possible. Tesla=E2=80=99s stock closed down yesterday, I guess on the th=
reat of massive sales.There are other options. A traditional leveraged buyo=
ut of Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0buy Twitter with money borrowed against Twitte=
r=E2=80=99s business =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems implausible for reasons we discus=
sed on Tuesday; Twitter just doesn=E2=80=99t have that much debt capacity. =
(It has a few billion dollars of bonds outstanding, but those would have to=
 be  paid back at a premium if Musk bought Twitter, further increasing the =
cash needed to do the deal.)Enlisting an equity partner to write a big part=
 of the check seems tough =E2=80=94=C2=A0why be the junior partner on Elon =
Musk=E2=80=99s whimsical trolling expedition, in which he has said publicly=
 that =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t care about the economics at all=E2=80=9D?=C2=
=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0though the Wall Street Journal reports that =E2=80=9CMr. =
Musk has heard from outside investors who may be interested in teaming up f=
or his bid.=E2=80=9D Perhaps some equity partner will take a gamble on the =
possibility that, at a private Twitter, Musk will be in charge of memes and=
 trolling, and his partner will be in charge of, like, finances and strateg=
y.=C2=A0Or perhaps he could get a league of libertarian billionaires togeth=
er to buy Twitter as their collective toy.Or Musk could=C2=A0borrow more ag=
ainst his Tesla stake. Tesla=E2=80=99s own policies prohibit Musk from borr=
owing more than 25% of the value of his shares, which is=C2=A0barely enough=
 to buy Twitter, even ignoring the fact that he has already used at least s=
ome of that capacity. Of course he=E2=80=99s in charge of Tesla and its boa=
rd is famously deferential to him, so I guess he could change those policie=
s, but that still requires finding a bank to lend him $40 billion against h=
is Tesla stake to finance=C2=A0this lark. Tesla=E2=80=99s stock has quadrup=
led since mid-2020; if it fell back to mid-2020 levels =E2=80=94=C2=A0say b=
ecause its charismatic attention-seeking CEO found a new toy =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then the loan would be underwater, and selling out of a gigantic Tesla m=
argin loan does not seem like a lot of fun for a bank.You can patch these t=
hings together =E2=80=94=C2=A0some Tesla margin borrowing, some Tesla sales=
, some Twitter leverage, some equity partners, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and prob=
ably get to $40 billion, but the financing seems tricky.=C2=A0And when he w=
as asked directly about it in public, Musk did not exactly try to reassure =
anyone; he didn=E2=80=99t say he had financing, and he did say =E2=80=9CI a=
m not sure that I will actually be able to acquire it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That s=
aid, his securities filing does say that he has hired Morgan Stanley as his=
 financial adviser. Presumably they are=C2=A0aware=C2=A0of this; like, they=
 are investment bankers and understand that if you sign a deal to pay $40 b=
illion for a company you need to come up with $40 billion. Presumably they =
want to earn a fee, which ordinarily only happens if you do a deal, so they=
 have some reason to be confident, and some incentive to stretch to provide=
 financing themselves. Lending the world=E2=80=99s richest man a few billio=
n dollars to earn an M&A fee would not be all that weird a move for a bank =
to make.=C2=A0And Twitter  has engaged Goldman Sachs Group Inc. to evaluate=
 his bid; they also understand this and will, you know, ask.=C2=A0Still I i=
magine that=C2=A0Twitter's bankers at Goldman Sachs will sit down with Musk=
's bankers at Morgan Stanley and Goldman will say =E2=80=9Cso uh where's th=
e financing coming from=E2=80=9D and Morgan Stanley will say =E2=80=9Coh th=
e financing is in this can=E2=80=9D and hand Goldman a can and Goldman will=
 open the can and a bunch of fake snakes will pop out. =E2=80=9CAAAHHH,=E2=
=80=9D Goldman will scream, and then they will chuckle and=C2=A0say =E2=80=
=9Coh Elon, you got us again=E2=80=9D and everyone will have a good laugh. =
Because, again, uniquely among public-company CEOs, Elon Musk has in the pa=
st pretended he was going to take a public company private with pretend fin=
ancing! I am not saying that he=E2=80=99s joking now; I am just saying he=
=E2=80=99s the only person who has ever made this particular joke in the pa=
st.Part of Goldman=E2=80=99s job here is surely to kick the tires on Musk=
=E2=80=99s deal, open the can of snakes etc. Another part is surely to find=
 a better deal.=C2=A0This is an awkward situation for Twitter's board. They=
 can=E2=80=99t really accept Musk's offer. For one thing the price is embar=
rassingly low; again, Twitter traded above the offer price last October. Fo=
r another thing, the financing seems to be made up of cobwebs and phlogisto=
n. But also=C2=A0Musk has joked about taking companies private before, and =
he generally changes his mind a lot. (He agreed to  join Twitter=E2=80=99s =
board last week! And then changed his mind  four days later!) If you are a =
well-advised professional public company board, it is just catastrophic to =
imagine that you might say =E2=80=9Cokay Elon $54.20 it is=E2=80=9D and the=
n he=E2=80=99d say =E2=80=9Cha no I was kidding, psych!=E2=80=9D That would=
 be crippling for a public company. Also that is basically what he did to T=
witter=E2=80=99s board last weekend!=C2=A0But it=E2=80=99s not easy to tell=
 Musk to get lost either. The price is embarrassingly low, yes, but it also=
 is well above where Twitter was trading pre-Musk; the embarrassment is lar=
gely Twitter=E2=80=99s fault. =E2=80=9CThis is an opportunistic lowball bid=
 that doesn't reflect the true long-term value of the company=E2=80=9D is a=
 pretty standard thing for a board to say when faced with a bid like this, =
and I sympathize with it here =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=C2=A0is an opportunistic lo=
wball bid! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if that=E2=80=99s your position you have to=
=C2=A0convince people of that long-term standalone value. =E2=80=9CTwitter =
is in really good hands right now and there=E2=80=99s no need to let Musk m=
ess with it=E2=80=9D is not a=C2=A0hugely=C2=A0compelling answer. Its CEO, =
Parag Agrawal, only recently replaced=C2=A0its charismatic but controversia=
l founder Jack Dorsey, and it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Twitter ...=C2=A0so it=E2=
=80=99s hard to fend off a hostile offer by saying=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cno, we=E2=
=80=99re good, everything=E2=80=99s perfect here.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Twitter cou=
ld counter with a more reasonable number, $69 or whatever. Musk=E2=80=99s l=
etter says that $54.20 is his =E2=80=9Cbest and final offer,=E2=80=9D and h=
is script for the board says=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI am not playing the back-and-fo=
rth game. I=C2=A0have moved straight to the end.=E2=80=9D One possibility i=
s that he is just saying this; it is after all a common enough thing to say=
 even if you don=E2=80=99t mean it. (If the highest price you=E2=80=99d pay=
 is $69, you might as well bid $54 and see what happens, and if you do that=
 there=E2=80=99s generally no reason to say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m bidding $5=
4 but I could do $69 if you=E2=80=99d rather.=E2=80=9D) Another possibility=
 is that he is serious, he won=E2=80=99t go a penny above $54.20, and if th=
e board says =E2=80=9Cwhat about $69=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s a nice face-sa=
ving way for everyone=C2=A0to walk away from this without (1) Musk buying T=
witter, (2) the board fighting a scorched-earth battle=C2=A0to prevent that=
, or (3) Musk having to say =E2=80=9Cyeah I was kidding.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But =
the most classic move for Twitter and its advisers here would be to use Mus=
k=E2=80=99s bid to kick off an auction. Arguably=C2=A0what has happened her=
e is that Musk has=C2=A0put Twitter in play, that after his bid it has to b=
e sold, but not to him. I don=E2=80=99t know to whom, and this is not an ea=
sy gig for Goldman, given that Twitter is just as big and hard to finance f=
or anyone else as it is for Musk. The obvious answer is another big cash-ri=
ch tech company, but that raises other problems. Mark Cuban tweeted=C2=A0th=
at =E2=80=9Cevery major tech company, Google, [Meta], et al. is on the phon=
e with their antitrust lawyers asking if they can buy Twitter and get it ap=
proved. And Twitter is on the phone with their lawyers asking which can be =
their white knight.=E2=80=9D Meanwhile I  wrote on Tuesday, about a then-hy=
pothetical Musk bid:Other than the money, though, there is not much about T=
witter that would prevent a takeover. It does not have dual-class stock tha=
t would keep its founders in control, and the founders are no longer in cha=
rge and don=E2=80=99t even=C2=A0own that much stock. It is not in a heavily=
 regulated industry,=C2=A0and there=E2=80=99s no particular antitrust probl=
em with=C2=A0Musk acquiring it. =E2=80=9CWorld=E2=80=99s richest person acq=
uires the main venue for public communication=E2=80=9D does=C2=A0seem=C2=A0=
like the sort of thing that ought to=C2=A0raise regulatory concerns, but in=
 our actually existing system I=E2=80=99m not sure what those concerns=C2=
=A0would be.=C2=A0Again it seems weird to me that the richest person in the=
 world buying the =E2=80=9Ctown square=E2=80=9D (his words) to privatize it=
 is just fine, while any realistic public-company buyer might run into anti=
trust trouble, but here we are.=C2=A0A few other points. First, who would b=
e the CEO of a Musk-owned Twitter? He has indicated that he wants to replac=
e current management. He has=C2=A0a number of other full-time jobs himself,=
 so is probably not available. But he clearly wants=C2=A0to meddle. What a =
terrible job running Twitter for him would be. A few levels down, who is go=
ing to run Twitter=E2=80=99s anti-abuse, trust and safety etc. functions, w=
hen Musk has made it clear he doesn=E2=80=99t believe in them? (=E2=80=9CTh=
ere is no way you unlock the value of Twitter by making it 99.9% porn, fake=
 Ray-Ban and male enhancement ads,=E2=80=9D tweeted Alex Stamos.)Second: Mu=
sk=C2=A0tweeted a poll, of course, asking if =E2=80=9CTaking Twitter privat=
e at $54.20 should be up to shareholders, not the board.=E2=80=9D Well! Tra=
ditionally, there are two ways to take a company private. You can propose a=
 merger, which by law=C2=A0has to go to the=C2=A0board for approval; the di=
rectors consider the offer as fiduciaries for the shareholders, and if they=
 approve=C2=A0then it goes to the shareholders for a vote. Or you can launc=
h a tender offer, which=C2=A0does not have to be approved by the board; you=
 make the offer directly to the shareholders, and if they all sell you thei=
r stock then you own the company. I am oversimplifying in various ways, and=
 in modern U.S. mergers-and-acquisitions practice the differences are not n=
early that stark. Most tender offers get board approval first, and if you d=
o a hostile tender offer the board=C2=A0can=C2=A0generally stop you by impl=
ementing a  poison pill. (And boards can be pressured by hostile bidders in=
to approving mergers.)=C2=A0So surprise hostile tender offers are rare in m=
odern practice, and it is natural that Musk=E2=80=99s first step was a =E2=
=80=9Cbear hug=E2=80=9D letter to the board.But it is the case that Musk co=
uld put a lot more pressure on Twitter=E2=80=99s board if he announced an a=
ll-cash tender offer at $54.20 per share than he actually did by sending th=
em a vague nonbinding letter. For one thing, a tender offer is generally vi=
ewed as more=C2=A0binding:=C2=A0If you send a nonbinding letter to the boar=
d you can always say =E2=80=9Cnever mind=E2=80=9D; if you send a tender off=
er to the shareholders you will have a harder time doing that. So sharehold=
ers and boards have to take it more seriously.=C2=A0For another thing, a te=
nder offer will include lots of detailed disclosure about things like =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0well, for our purposes, mainly it will include detailed disclos=
ure about where the money is coming from. Which Musk=E2=80=99s offer pointe=
dly does not!In other words, if Musk actually=C2=A0wanted=C2=A0the decision=
 on this deal to be made by=C2=A0shareholders, not the board, he could act =
like it. He has not! He is acting like he wants=C2=A0the decision on this d=
eal to be made by a poll of his Twitter followers, which is not at all how =
M&A works.Third: What if the board says =E2=80=9Cno, never, not in a millio=
n years=E2=80=9D? Musk could go more hostile:=C2=A0Do a tender, run a proxy=
 fight, try to get shareholders to pressure the board, etc. Again, he doesn=
=E2=80=99t seem all that interested in that, and neither do the shareholder=
s. But it=E2=80=99s certainly possible.Or he could sell his stock. Which is=
 what he said he would do; from his offer letter: =E2=80=9CMy offer is my b=
est and final offer and if it is not accepted, I would need to reconsider m=
y position as a shareholder.=E2=80=9D And: =E2=80=9CIf the deal doesn=E2=80=
=99t work, given that I don=E2=80=99t have confidence in management nor do =
I believe I can drive the necessary change in the public market, I would ne=
ed to reconsider my position as a shareholder. This is not a threat, it's s=
imply not a good investment without the changes that need to be made.=E2=80=
=9DNow, I cannot resist pointing out that=C2=A0two weeks ago Musk  filed a =
Schedule 13G indicating that he had bought 9% of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock as=
 a  passive investment with no intention to cause a change in control. If h=
e bought the stock to make management changes, he would have had=C2=A0to fi=
le a different, more detailed form, Schedule 13D.=C2=A0People can change th=
eir minds! But if Twitter is not now a good investment without radical chan=
ges, then why did he buy it as a passive investment two weeks ago? What cha=
nged? (Also the 13G was late.) Musk is not even gesturing in the direction =
of minimal compliance with securities laws at this point. This doesn=E2=80=
=99t have=C2=A0much to do with whether or not his bid will succeed, and I d=
o not expect that the Securities and Exchange Commission can or will do muc=
h about it. But it is=C2=A0annoying!If he does sell the stock, I don=E2=80=
=99t quite know what that looks like. One possibility is that he sells out,=
 quickly and quietly, after the board rejects his offer but before the stoc=
k price goes all the way down to pre-Musk levels, that by drawing attention=
 to Twitter he made it a meme stock and will make a quick profit.[1] Anothe=
r=C2=A0possibility, more likely I think, is that if this deal=C2=A0dies the=
n Twitter falls to=C2=A0below=C2=A0pre-Musk levels =E2=80=94=C2=A0before Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s adventure, Twitter=E2=80=99s price reflected=C2=A0some=C2=A0pr=
obability of a takeover; if Musk kicks the tires and no deal happens then t=
hat probability is lowered =E2=80=94=C2=A0and he sells out at a loss. A thi=
rd possibility is that Twitter finds some friendly white knight to buy Musk=
=E2=80=99s stake as a block at a mutually non-embarrassing price. A fourth =
possibility is that he sells down to exactly 69,420,000 shares and goes bac=
k to filing a 13G and smirking.I don=E2=80=99t know what Twitter does in an=
y of those situations. There is no particularly good outcome for Twitter he=
re. It can sell to Musk and become (more of) a vehicle for his whims and tr=
olling. It can find some other imperfect buyer and try to cobble a desperat=
ion=C2=A0deal together. Or it can (maybe) fend off Musk, stay independent, =
watch its stock drop, alienate one of its most high-profile users, and get =
second-guessed by shareholders for years. Twitter is in play, but that is o=
nly really fun for Musk.Anyway I really truly am on vacation but I assume t=
hat by Monday Elon Musk will have somehow acquired Money Stuff. In a sense =
he already has.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy ema=
il form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you ca=
n subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Than=
ks![1] People keep emailing me to suggest that Musk might be doing some sor=
t of =E2=80=9Cpump and dump,=E2=80=9D where his bid is an elaborate ruse to=
 push up the price of Twitter stock so he can sell at a profit. I do not bu=
y this. For one thing, I think it would be tricky for him to sell while the=
 market still expects a deal; he can=E2=80=99t trade while he has material =
nonpublic information. But more important,=C2=A0Musk just doesn=E2=80=99t o=
perate that way. He has amply demonstrated his ability to manipulate the pr=
ice of many financial assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0Tesla stock, Bitcoin, Dogecoin,=
 Twitter stock, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I do not think he has ever used=
 that ability to make a quick buck. If he comes away from this escapade wit=
h an extra, like, $500 million and no Twitter, what does that accomplish fo=
r him?
