ard says =E2=80=9Cwhat about $69=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s a nice face-saving=
 way for everyone=C2=A0to walk away from this without (1) Musk buying Twitt=
er, (2) the board fighting a scorched-earth battle=C2=A0to prevent that, or=
 (3) Musk having to say =E2=80=9Cyeah I was kidding.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the most classic move for Twitter and its advi=
sers here would be to use Musk=E2=80=99s bid to kick off an auction. Arguab=
ly=C2=A0what has happened here is that Musk has=C2=A0<em>put Twitter in pla=
y</em>, that after his bid it has to be sold, but not to him. I don=E2=80=
=99t know to whom, and this is not an easy gig for Goldman, given that Twit=
ter is just as big and hard to finance for anyone else as it is for Musk. T=
he obvious answer is another big cash-rich tech company, but that raises ot=
her problems. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2738=
1871.266597/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tY3ViYW4vc3RhdHVzLzE1MTQ2MDk5MzQ4OTc=
zMzYzMjQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB57766eb4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
