or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">tweeted A=
lex Stamos</a>.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second: <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27381871.266597/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVy=
LmNvbS9lbG9ubXVzay9zdGF0dXMvMTUxNDY5ODAzNjc2MDUzMDk0NT9zPTExJnQ9QVFVeldvb2R=
INWQxWlhQcTlmcEdxZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbe5aeae8" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Musk=C2=A0<e=
m>tweeted a poll</em></a>, of course, asking if =E2=80=9CTaking Twitter pri=
vate at $54.20 should be up to shareholders, not the board.=E2=80=9D Well! =
Traditionally, there are two ways to take a company private. You can propos=
e a merger, which <em>by law=C2=A0has to go to the=C2=A0board for approval<=
/em>; the directors consider the offer as fiduciaries for the shareholders,=
 and if they approve=C2=A0then it goes to the shareholders for a vote. Or y=
ou can launch a tender offer, which=C2=A0<em>does not have to be approved b=
y the board</em>; you make the offer directly to the shareholders, and if t=
hey all sell you their stock then you own the company. I am oversimplifying=
 in various ways, and in modern U.S. mergers-and-acquisitions practice the =
differences are not nearly that stark. Most tender offers get board approva=
l first, and if you do a hostile tender offer the board=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0<=
/em>generally stop you by implementing a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/27381871.266597/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
ZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMTQvdHdpdHRlci1pcy1zYWlkLXRvLXdlaWdoLXBvaXNvbi1=
waWxsLWRlZmVuc2UtdG8tdGh3YXJ0LW11c2stYmlkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTUyMl9NT05FWVNUVU=
ZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDQxN=
SZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB34e48580" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> poison pill</a>. (And boards can be pressured by hostile bidders into ap=
proving mergers.)=C2=A0So surprise hostile tender offers are rare in modern=
 practice, and it is natural that Musk=E2=80=99s first step was a =E2=80=9C=
bear hug=E2=80=9D letter to the board.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But =
it is the case that Musk could put a lot more pressure on Twitter=E2=80=99s=
 board if he announced an all-cash tender offer at $54.20 per share than he=
 actually did by sending them a vague nonbinding letter. For one thing, a t=
ender offer is generally viewed as more=C2=A0<em>binding:=C2=A0</em>If you =
send a nonbinding letter to the board you can always say =E2=80=9Cnever min=
d=E2=80=9D; if you send a tender offer to the shareholders you will have a =
harder time doing that. So shareholders and boards have to take it more ser=
iously.=C2=A0For another thing, a tender offer will include lots of detaile=
d disclosure about things like =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, for our purposes, mainl=
y it will include detailed disclosure about where the money is coming from.=
 Which Musk=E2=80=99s offer pointedly does not!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">In other words, if Musk actually=C2=A0<em>wanted=C2=A0</em>the decisio=
n on this deal to be made by=C2=A0shareholders, not the board, he could act=
 like it. He has not! He is acting like he wants=C2=A0the decision on this =
deal to be made by a poll of his Twitter followers, which is not at all how=
 M&amp;A works.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third: What if the board sa=
ys =E2=80=9Cno, never, not in a million years=E2=80=9D? Musk could go more =
hostile:=C2=A0Do a tender, run a proxy fight, try to get shareholders to pr=
essure the board, etc. Again, he doesn=E2=80=99t seem all that interested i=
n that, and neither do the shareholders. But it=E2=80=99s certainly possibl=
e.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or he could sell his stock. Which is wha=
t he said he would do; from his offer letter: =E2=80=9CMy offer is my best =
and final offer and if it is not accepted, I would need to reconsider my po=
sition as a shareholder.=E2=80=9D And: =E2=80=9CIf the deal doesn=E2=80=99t=
 work, given that I don=E2=80=99t have confidence in management nor do I be=
lieve I can drive the necessary change in the public market, I would need t=
o reconsider my position as a shareholder. This is not a threat, it's simpl=
y not a good investment without the changes that need to be made.=E2=80=9D<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, I cannot resist pointing out that=C2=
=A0<em>two weeks ago </em>Musk <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/27381871.266597/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMDQvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWJvdWdodC1zb21lLXR3aXR0ZXI_Y21waWQ9Q=
kJEMDQxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0=
ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB60fad11b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> filed a Schedule 13G</a> indicating that he had b=
ought 9% of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock as a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/27381871.266597/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMDYvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWlzLWFjdGl2ZS1ub3c_Y21waWQ=
9QkJEMDQxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZX=
R0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB7b9fb3ef" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> passive investment</a> with no intention to cau=
se a change in control. If he bought the stock to make management changes, =
he would have had=C2=A0to file a different, more detailed form, Schedule 13=
D.=C2=A0People can change their minds! But if Twitter is not now a good inv=
estment without radical changes, then why did he buy it as a passive invest=
ment two weeks ago? What changed? (Also the 13G was late.) Musk is not even=
 gesturing in the direction of minimal compliance with securities laws at t=
his point. This doesn=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0much to do with whether or not hi=
s bid will succeed, and I do not expect that the Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission can or will do much about it. But it is=C2=A0annoying!</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If he does sell the stock, I don=E2=80=99t quite know =
what that looks like. One possibility is that he sells out, quickly and qui=
etly, after the board rejects his offer but before the stock price goes all=
 the way down to pre-Musk levels, that by drawing attention to Twitter he m=
ade it a meme stock and will make a quick profit.[1] Another=C2=A0possibili=
ty, more likely I think, is that if this deal=C2=A0dies then Twitter falls =
to=C2=A0<em>below=C2=A0</em>pre-Musk levels =E2=80=94=C2=A0before Musk=E2=
=80=99s adventure, Twitter=E2=80=99s price reflected=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</e=
m>probability of a takeover; if Musk kicks the tires and no deal happens th=
en that probability is lowered =E2=80=94=C2=A0and he sells out at a loss. A=
 third possibility is that Twitter finds some friendly white knight to buy =
Musk=E2=80=99s stake as a block at a mutually non-embarrassing price. A fou=
rth possibility is that he sells down to exactly 69,420,000 shares and goes=
 back to filing a 13G and smirking.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=
=E2=80=99t know what Twitter does in any of those situations. There is no p=
articularly good outcome for Twitter here. It can sell to Musk and become (=
more of) a vehicle for his whims and trolling. It can find some other imper=
fect buyer and try to cobble a desperation=C2=A0deal together. Or it can (m=
aybe) fend off Musk, stay independent, watch its stock drop, alienate one o=
f its most high-profile users, and get second-guessed by shareholders for y=
ears. Twitter is in play, but that is only really fun for Musk.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway I really truly am on vacation but I assume that=
 by Monday Elon Musk will have somehow acquired Money Stuff. In a sense he =
already has.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><span class=3D"news-designed-f=
or-consumer-media"><em>If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in h=
andy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
